59
00:03:29,531 --> 00:03:41,110
Scott: Yeah, well I mean, there was, basically the idea of Steam Greenlight, if you don't know, is Steam has a problem in that they want the awesomest games to be on Steam, but they don't want it to be the Apple Store where all the crap in the universe is on Steam.

60
00:03:41,230 --> 00:03:44,490
Scott: They want to pick and choose, you know, the good stuff to be on there.

61
00:03:44,630 --> 00:03:50,309
Rym: Yeah, ever try to search for a game on the Apple Store if you didn't already know the name of the game you were looking for?

62
00:03:50,470 --> 00:03:59,728
Scott: Right, so, you know, but the problem is they don't have enough manpower at Valve to know which games are to look at, you know, there's so many games they can't look at 'em all, so what do they even do about that?

63
00:04:00,230 --> 00:04:01,790
Scott: You know, so they crowdsource it.

64
00:04:01,910 --> 00:04:09,249
Scott: They basically sort of make a Reddit-ish of, you know, game submissions, and the games that get voted all the way up are the ones they'll take a look at to see if they can get 'em on Steam.

65
00:04:09,771 --> 00:04:10,289
Scott: Great idea.

66
00:04:11,230 --> 00:04:11,609
Scott: Problem.

67
00:04:12,211 --> 00:04:15,070
Scott: Day one, they put this up, and it's full of crap.

68
00:04:15,532 --> 00:04:21,209
Rym: We're not talking crap like- We're talking like straight up spam, like Viagra spam that pretended to be a game.

69
00:04:21,430 --> 00:04:25,310
Scott: Like somebody posting Call of Duty in like Russia.

70
00:04:25,573 --> 00:04:26,210
Scott: It's like, what?

71
00:04:26,531 --> 00:04:32,569
Rym: It's not- Scott, I'm reminded, so I ask you this, is this Battletoads?

72
00:04:32,990 --> 00:04:33,699
Scott: Yeah, it's just Battletoads.

73
00:04:35,992 --> 00:04:38,346
Scott: So anyway, so they're like, "Shit, what do we do about this,

74
00:04:38,386 --> 00:04:38,648
Scott: guys?".

75
00:04:39,130 --> 00:04:46,570
Scott: So Valve decided what they would do, and this had nothing to do, as you might think, Valve did not talk to the Penny Arcade people about this at all.

76
00:04:46,610 --> 00:04:49,251
Scott: They just did it entirely on their own, 100%.

77
00:04:49,251 --> 00:04:58,410
Scott: They decided that if you want to submit your game to Greenlight, you have to donate $100 to Child's Play, and then your game will be listed on Greenlight.

78
00:04:58,550 --> 00:05:02,410
Scott: So that way, it's sort of a filter that only a serious submission will go on there.

79
00:05:02,430 --> 00:05:05,390
Rym: Now, the way it works is you pay Valve, and they just pass all the money to Child's Play.

80
00:05:05,573 --> 00:05:05,950
Scott: Exactly.

81
00:05:06,110 --> 00:05:06,849
Scott: So it's just a fee.

82
00:05:06,910 --> 00:05:07,668
Scott: There's no profit for them.

83
00:05:07,970 --> 00:05:13,470
Rym: Now, what amazed me was the gaming community's outrage at this.

84
00:05:13,650 --> 00:05:17,250
Scott: Well, basically their outrage was, "Look, these are indie developers.

85
00:05:17,413 --> 00:05:18,290
Scott: They have no money.

86
00:05:18,451 --> 00:05:22,387
Scott: Even if their game is successful, they'll have no fucking money, because it sucks

87
00:05:22,448 --> 00:05:22,809
Scott: balls.".

88
00:05:23,030 --> 00:05:23,695
Scott: Well, here's the thing.

89
00:05:23,695 --> 00:05:29,410
Rym: $100, if you're not serious, is a lot of money.

90
00:05:30,330 --> 00:05:31,929
Scott: And if you don't have a real job.

91
00:05:33,252 --> 00:05:41,030
Rym: Even then, if I was going to make t-shirts for GeekNights, the few hundred dollars it costs to print the first run before I sell them, I'm not going to shoulder that burden.

92
00:05:41,210 --> 00:05:46,210
Rym: But seriously, pretty much everything but the bottomest, bottomest tier.

93
00:05:46,350 --> 00:05:50,430
Rym: If you make a game that's worthy enough to be on Steam, you can afford the hundred bucks.

94
00:05:50,810 --> 00:05:52,349
Rym: You're going to make the hundred bucks back.

95
00:05:52,891 --> 00:05:58,370
Scott: Yeah, the only thing I could say to that is it could be 20 bucks, right?

96
00:05:58,773 --> 00:05:59,609
Rym: I don't think so.

97
00:06:00,210 --> 00:06:06,110
Scott: Who's going to ... But nobody ... 20 bucks is going to keep out the Call of Duty submission.

98
00:06:06,730 --> 00:06:09,990
Rym: So Steam is not the venue for everything.

99
00:06:10,110 --> 00:06:10,969
Rym: What is their other goal?

100
00:06:11,271 --> 00:06:12,609
Rym: To keep all the crap out.

101
00:06:13,090 --> 00:06:21,427
Rym: I hate to say this, if you cannot muster $100, your game probably not is above the minimum line of, "I would ever bother with it on

102
00:06:21,467 --> 00:06:21,749
Rym: Steam.".

103
00:06:22,192 --> 00:06:25,850
Rym: That's the level of game that I download from your website.

104
00:06:27,292 --> 00:06:28,428
Scott: You know, it's a tough call.

105
00:06:28,590 --> 00:06:36,230
Rym: Also, if a game is that diamond in the rough where it really is worth being on Steam, people You can get the hundred dollars from somebody else.

106
00:06:36,692 --> 00:06:40,290
Rym: Yes, and you don't have a hundred dollars, you could kickstart for that hundred bucks.

107
00:06:40,710 --> 00:06:47,830
Scott: Yeah, it's like if you've got ... If your game is worthy and you got some demo video or something, you'll get the hundred dollars from somebody.

108
00:06:47,830 --> 00:06:49,490
Rym: So if you are too poor to get the money.

109
00:06:49,530 --> 00:06:53,370
Scott: Do think that you could lower it and still get the same filtration effect in it.

110
00:06:53,570 --> 00:06:54,530
Scott: Like 50 bucks, no problem.

111
00:06:54,690 --> 00:06:56,690
Rym: See, that's why I'm saying it's serving two purposes.

112
00:06:56,990 --> 00:07:01,950
Rym: Kind of like how a captcha that involves logic or reasoning of some kind serves two purposes.

113
00:07:02,390 --> 00:07:05,109
Rym: A regular captcha nominally exists only to keep robots out.

114
00:07:05,912 --> 00:07:09,190
Rym: But a slightly complex captcha also keeps idiots out.

115
00:07:10,034 --> 00:07:11,490
Rym: That is a very important function.

116
00:07:12,191 --> 00:07:24,710
Rym: If you can't afford the 20 bucks and you cannot get $20 from anyone, you cannot get anyone you know in the world to help you pony up a hundred bucks to get your game on Steam.

117
00:07:25,090 --> 00:07:28,290
Scott: What if you're from another country where a hundred dollars is literally like a fuck ton of money?

118
00:07:29,471 --> 00:07:30,950
Rym: Even then, you can't get someone.

119
00:07:31,190 --> 00:07:33,710
Rym: You can't get some person somewhere.

120
00:07:34,173 --> 00:07:34,909
Scott: From a rich country.

121
00:07:35,390 --> 00:07:35,766
Rym: Anywhere.

122
00:07:37,190 --> 00:07:45,470
Rym: I feel like it's just to cut down on the total number of even, you know, relatively okay or they are actually a game, even if they're a bad game submissions.

123
00:07:46,133 --> 00:07:52,950
Rym: Because green light is useless unless the submissions are low enough for one or two people to go through all of them all the time that make it to the top.

124
00:07:53,570 --> 00:07:56,970
Rym: And to curate it a little bit and make sure something crazy doesn't happen and whatever.

125
00:07:57,770 --> 00:08:04,650
Rym: The other thing is, you know, I kind of mentioned this before, but the gaming community seems to have completely missed the real reason for this.

126
00:08:04,770 --> 00:08:13,910
Rym: It's not so that a game that is great will guaranteed be on Steam because games that are great that anyone notices will get on Steam anyway.

127
00:08:13,950 --> 00:08:17,390
Rym: If there's any game that is not noticed, it's probably going to get on Steam.

128
00:08:17,570 --> 00:08:28,610
Rym: Let's say someone in a very poor country makes a game and they can't get the hundred bucks and there's no way, some magical world where they cannot in any capacity get anyone to believe in them enough to help them get a hundred bucks.

129
00:08:29,690 --> 00:08:39,448
Rym: If anyone even finds the game and realizes that it's good, it'll still get on there because Valve can just take a game and reach out to people and say, "Hey, let's do

130
00:08:39,528 --> 00:08:39,568
Rym: it.".

131
00:08:40,030 --> 00:08:42,490
Rym: This is only to catch games that Valve didn't notice.

132
00:08:43,570 --> 00:08:44,052
Scott: That's true.

133
00:08:45,415 --> 00:08:50,790
Scott: So, speaking of Steam, in the Steam beta, there's two really interesting things.

134
00:08:51,010 --> 00:08:55,750
Scott: One of them everyone knows about is big picture mode, which is Steam working on your TV.

135
00:08:56,972 --> 00:08:57,722
Scott: I tried it out.

136
00:08:57,762 --> 00:08:58,269
Scott: Did you try it out?

137
00:08:58,431 --> 00:08:59,009
Rym: I did not yet.

138
00:08:59,250 --> 00:08:59,996
Scott: So here's how it works.

139
00:09:00,097 --> 00:09:01,489
Scott: First, you've got to activate Steam beta.

140
00:09:01,670 --> 00:09:03,821
Scott: To do that, you go to Steam settings.

141
00:09:04,203 --> 00:09:05,570
Scott: Yes, I want to participate in the beta.

142
00:09:05,670 --> 00:09:09,390
Scott: You restart Steam and then in the top right of Steam, you can activate big picture.

143
00:09:09,491 --> 00:09:12,930
Rym: I saw that there's a Steam mover replacement in there.

144
00:09:13,190 --> 00:09:13,675
Scott: Well, hold on.

145
00:09:13,695 --> 00:09:14,990
Scott: That's the second thing I'm talking about.

146
00:09:15,330 --> 00:09:23,061
Scott: So, you activate big picture and then you push the button and the Steam takes up your whole screen and it's sort of like using your Xbox with your gamepad, right?

147
00:09:24,890 --> 00:09:27,330
Scott: It's like this user interface to navigate Steam from your couch.

148
00:09:28,111 --> 00:09:29,174
Scott: It has a web browser.

149
00:09:29,655 --> 00:09:36,630
Scott: It's not a good web browser, but it's the best web browser you can make with a gamepad, which is pretty impressive, right?

150
00:09:36,730 --> 00:09:41,990
Scott: It's like, man, this real user interface is really bad for browsing the web, but this is the best you could do.

151
00:09:42,210 --> 00:09:53,850
Rym: You know, I've always said, and as Yumi and Connor had talked about at length at PAX, if anyone's going to make a thing that will be the PC/HTPC gaming console that is generic, it'll be Valve.

152
00:09:54,651 --> 00:09:58,490
Scott: The best thing about it is the way you type without a keyboard.

153
00:09:58,970 --> 00:10:09,090
Scott: Basically, you enter a text box or something and this thing shows up on the screen and you use the left stick to select a blob and the blobs are in a big radius, so it's a radial menu.

154
00:10:09,790 --> 00:10:14,690
Scott: And each blob has four letters and the four letters map to the four buttons on the right side of the gamepad.

155
00:10:15,110 --> 00:10:22,847
Scott: So you hold into the top right blob and that'll have like H, J, K, L. So it's like red is H, yellow is J, blue is...

156
00:10:23,390 --> 00:10:24,494
Rym: Oh my god, that's really nice.

157
00:10:24,554 --> 00:10:29,030
Rym: I just had flashbacks to the days of trying to type in a Metal Gear password without fucking it up.

158
00:10:29,110 --> 00:10:35,350
Scott: Right, so it's like, man, if Nintendo would have come up with that back in the NES days for typing in passwords.

159
00:10:36,250 --> 00:10:39,650
Scott: But I guess it was only eight directions, not enough really.

160
00:10:39,930 --> 00:10:43,510
Scott: Eight times two buttons is only sixteen possible letters.

161
00:10:43,750 --> 00:10:45,581
Rym: So you make passwords that only have sixteen.

162
00:10:45,601 --> 00:10:51,770
Rym: The thing is, it's interesting, I feel like kids who were playing games in that era could not have dealt with that.

163
00:10:52,170 --> 00:10:54,663
Scott: No, and the user interface wouldn't have updated quickly.

164
00:10:55,125 --> 00:10:56,170
Scott: Maybe you could make it anyway.

165
00:10:56,551 --> 00:10:57,914
Scott: The point is, it's a really good typing thing.

166
00:10:58,255 --> 00:11:07,803
Scott: The rest of it, basically when you open a game that supports gamepads by default, and is full screen by default, it's beautiful.

167
00:11:07,863 --> 00:11:09,350
Scott: It's like you're using a console.

168
00:11:09,550 --> 00:11:13,890
Scott: It's like you go "boop" and a game opens full screen and your gamepad is still working and it's great.

169
00:11:14,450 --> 00:11:32,070
Scott: When you open a game that is default to opening in window mode, or maybe doesn't support gamepads at all, or you have to configure the gamepad before it'll work, then suddenly everything is immediately ruined, mostly, once you open that particular, launch that game.

170
00:11:32,210 --> 00:11:32,699
Rym: Well, one step at a time.

171
00:11:32,740 --> 00:11:33,250
Rym: It is a beta.

172
00:11:34,130 --> 00:11:36,282
Scott: Well, I mean, you can't do much about these games, though.

173
00:11:36,322 --> 00:11:37,630
Scott: You have to update all these games.

174
00:11:37,770 --> 00:11:51,150
Rym: Yeah, well I feel like one of the killer apps for the complete replacement of these consoles like the Xbox, where you actually just have a Steam box of some kind, will be when Valve helps developers not be dumbasses.

175
00:11:51,532 --> 00:11:55,170
Rym: There should never be a game where I have to use Joy to Key on Steam.

176
00:11:55,230 --> 00:11:58,530
Scott: But I'm talking about if you open up some old existing game.

177
00:11:58,810 --> 00:12:01,370
Scott: Future games probably will be, you know, but it's an existing game.

178
00:12:01,390 --> 00:12:02,051
Scott: Well, two things.

179
00:12:02,392 --> 00:12:10,670
Rym: One, I would do something on Valve where any game could be certified to be compatible with the big box mode, the big screen mode.

180
00:12:10,710 --> 00:12:13,909
Scott: Yeah, and then you could easily filter those games out of the list that aren't certified.

181
00:12:14,551 --> 00:12:27,050
Rym: What I might do is offer, like, come up with some tools that will make it relatively easy for people to get that certification, like to take their old game and, like, re-edit it to make it work with the gamepad and the full screen and everything.

182
00:12:28,030 --> 00:12:31,730
Rym: And then I'd find some third party, because you know what, Valve wouldn't want to do this themselves.

183
00:12:32,150 --> 00:12:37,650
Rym: Find some third party to partner with and have them be able to offer a service of, like, we'll make your game work.

184
00:12:37,670 --> 00:12:47,590
Scott: All you really need to do to have a game work properly in big picture is, when you launch it for the first time by default after installing it with default config, it needs to be full screen.

185
00:12:48,391 --> 00:12:56,150
Scott: It should be probably 1080p or 720p, detect the resolution from the OS, but it doesn't matter as much as just being full screen, because you can change the resolution.

186
00:12:56,430 --> 00:13:03,350
Scott: And B, you need to be able to navigate all the menus and do everything in the game with the gamepad, with the default configuration from the get-go.

187
00:13:04,131 --> 00:13:05,297
Scott: And that's all you really got to do.

188
00:13:05,317 --> 00:13:07,185
Scott: You've got those two things and that's it.

189
00:13:09,811 --> 00:13:17,087
Scott: But yeah, it was kind of nice, you know, and I'd probably use it for all of my Steam PC gaming.

190
00:13:17,127 --> 00:13:18,310
Scott: that was good for a gamepad.

191
00:13:18,650 --> 00:13:24,510
Scott: And I sort of organized all my Steam games into two lists, the gamepad HTPC games and the desktop games.

192
00:13:25,530 --> 00:13:33,150
Scott: And, you know, I realized most of those, one thing I realized is that most of those HTPC gamepad games were all, like, indie games.

193
00:13:33,911 --> 00:13:43,870
